reviews.text: Does it work? Yes. Would I buy this particular one again? No Why? There is literally zero resistance from the turning knob. So, if you bump it by mistake or slightly touch it, it will move and thus change the brightness of lights. Had to tape it with scotch tape to stay in place. Cheap quality and execution.

reviews.productTitle: Onite 2PCS LED Strip Dimmer Switch, USB Female to Male Extension Cord with Dimmable Rotary Switch
reviews.text: For my application I only needed the dimmer module, not the cords and enclosure it came with, as I wanted to integrate it into another enclosure. So I took it apart. I am glad I did though, as the connections were pretty bad. The PCB looks decent otherwise, but whoever soldered the USB leads on, did a bad job stripping the wire. It probably would never have a problem as the insides are not likely to shift, but you never know and even a short in 5v is enough for a bad time. I still kept it, but probably would not recommend due to the safety concern. They could easily fix this issue with a little quality control.
reviews.date: Reviewed in the United States on July 13, 2024
reviews.title: Quality control is a bit lacking...

reviews.productTitle: Onite 2PCS LED Strip Dimmer Switch, USB Female to Male Extension Cord with Dimmable Rotary Switch
reviews.text: 4 stars, because it does work. Connect it, turn the dial, and your device can go from off to barely on to full power. However -- I got it for an LED lamp that continuously cycles through a range of colors, and it turns out that in order to do that, the power has to be on max. I can have a red glow as dim as I want it, but the color change cycle won't start unless I turn up the power all the way. If I unplug it while on a different color, it comes on red again when I reconnect it, and stays that way unless I turn the power up. I realize this is my lamp's problem, not the dimmer, but since this is probably not an uncommon type of device to want to use this with, you should be warned it may not work for that.
reviews.date: Reviewed in the United States on October 18, 2021
reviews.title: Works, but not with everything
